    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.7.0\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNot applicable\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGNOME terminal\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nArch Linux Community repository\n\n### How to reproduce the issue\n\nCreate this file:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nvim.defer_fn(function()\r\n  vim.api.nvim_echo({ { '', '' } }, false, {})\r\nend, 5000)\r\n```\r\n\r\nNow open the file and run `:so %`, then immediately type `:echo 'test'` but _don't_ run the command. Instead, wait for up to 5 seconds, and observe how the input is hidden. The input appears again when you change it (e.g. by typing an extra character).\r\n\r\nThis can be seen here:\r\n\r\n[![asciicast](https://asciinema.org/a/ogeMsStVjETHiyrSOR01VH4ZI.svg)](https://asciinema.org/a/ogeMsStVjETHiyrSOR01VH4ZI)\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI would expect that echo'ing messages using `nvim_echo()` doesn't impact the commandline input. The regular `:echo` command appears to behave exactly that way.\n\n### Actual behavior\n\nThe input is \"hidden\", and re-appears when you change the commandline input.",
